{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5cd6e1c6-df3a-4382-b0ba-1ebc17d7eb8c","content":"Your project uses **xUnit v3** with **Microsoft.Testing.Platform** (MTP) enabled. Use this command:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~ShoppingCartTests\"\n```\n\nThe `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` property in your `.csproj` ensures `dotnet test` automatically translates the VSTest-style `--filter` into the MTP treenode filter format. The `~` operator means \"contains\", so this matches all tests in the `ShoppingCartTests` class.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7d7d4bc3-dead-4909-b3a8-b2040f9ade0f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is an xUnit v3 project with `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` enabled, meaning it uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP). The filter syntax for MTP with xUnit v3 is different from VSTest.\n\nFor MTP with xUnit v3, the filter syntax uses `--treenode-filter` or `--filter` depending on the version. Let me check the xUnit v3 docs. Actually, with `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport=true`, `dotnet test` translates `--filter` to the appropriate platform filter.\n\nFor xUnit v3 on MTP, the filter uses a treenode filter syntax like `/**/*ShoppingCartTests*/**` or similar.\n\n\nWith `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport=true`, the `--filter` argument passed to `dotnet test` gets translated to the MTP format, and the standard VSTest filter syntax like `FullyQualifiedName~ShoppingCartTests` should work for filtering by class name. should work with the VSTest-compatible filter syntax since `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` automatically translates it, though I could also use the MTP-specific treenode filter syntax directly if needed.","outputTokens":752,"requestId":"5C23:31910B:19805A:200983:69F55217"},"id":"f4cc2817-0b6c-4f3f-ba08-e843db9b90d5","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:23:55.605Z","parentId":"2e873975-4f59-4b00-896b-e1372b48f621"}
